      <h2>Mangu</h2>
      <p>Mangú is a beloved Dominican breakfast staple, cherished for its simplicity, rich flavors, and cultural
        significance. This dish is made from boiled green plantains that are mashed to a smooth, creamy consistency.
        Often enjoyed with a side of fried cheese, crispy salami, and sunny-side-up or scrambled eggs, Mangú offers a
        hearty, well-balanced meal that captures the essence of Dominican comfort food.</p>

      <p>The origins of Mangú trace back to the island's African heritage, reflecting the culinary traditions brought by
        enslaved Africans to the Caribbean. Over generations, this dish has evolved to become a cultural icon,
        symbolizing resilience, adaptability, and the melding of diverse influences that define Dominican cuisine.</p>

      The preparation of Mangú is straightforward yet precise. Green plantains are peeled, boiled with a pinch of
      salt, and mashed with a splash of water or butter to achieve a creamy texture. Some cooks also add onions
      sautéed in vinegar, which provides a tangy, aromatic topping that enhances the dish’s flavor profile. The
      accompaniments—fried cheese, salami, and eggs—add layers of taste and texture, making Mangú a complete and
      satisfying meal.</p>

      Beyond its role as a breakfast dish, Mangú holds a special place in the hearts of Dominicans and visitors alike.
      It is often associated with family gatherings, early morning meals, and celebrations, embodying the warmth and
      hospitality of Dominican culture. Whether served at a bustling "colmado" (corner store eatery) or prepared
      lovingly at home, Mangú is a dish that unites people across generations, offering a taste of tradition and home.
      Its enduring popularity highlights its importance as more than just food—Mangú is a symbol of Dominican identity
      and pride.</p>
