      <h2>Sancocho</h2>
      <p>Sancocho is one of the Dominican Republic's most cherished and iconic dishes, celebrated for its deep, rich
        flavors and its ability to bring people together. This hearty stew is a culinary masterpiece made with a variety
        of meats, such as chicken, pork, beef, and sometimes goat, combined with an array of root vegetables like yucca,
        plantains, taro, potatoes, and squash. Each ingredient contributes to the dish’s complexity, creating a
        flavorful and nourishing meal that reflects the nation’s cultural heritage.</p>

      <p>Often referred to as the ultimate comfort food, Sancocho is much more than just a stew—it is a symbol of unity
        and tradition. This dish is typically prepared for special occasions, such as family gatherings, birthdays,
        holidays, or community celebrations, and it plays a central role in Dominican culinary culture. The process of
        cooking Sancocho is as meaningful as the meal itself, with families and friends often coming together to peel,
        chop, and season ingredients, sharing stories and laughter along the way.</p>

      <p>The recipe for Sancocho varies by region and household, with each cook adding their unique twist. However,
        common ingredients include a savory broth seasoned with garlic, cilantro, oregano, and a hint of lime juice for
        brightness. The meats are slow-cooked to tender perfection, and the root vegetables absorb the broth’s flavors,
        creating a robust and satisfying dish. In its most elaborate form, Sancocho de Siete Carnes (Sancocho of Seven
        Meats) includes a combination of chicken, beef, pork, and other proteins, showcasing the dish's versatility and
        grandeur.</p>

      <p>Traditionally served with white rice and slices of ripe avocado, Sancocho is a complete meal that fills both
        the
        stomach and the soul. It embodies the warmth, resilience, and hospitality of Dominican culture, offering a taste
        of history and tradition in every bowl. Whether shared on a rainy day or during a festive gathering, Sancocho
        continues to be a beloved dish that connects generations and celebrates the richness of the Dominican Republic’s
        culinary heritage.</p>

